941,PingAn_3,How can investors and corporates leverage AI driven climate risk disclosure indicators Help asset managers structure meaningful decarbon- ization strategies: The asset management industry has by now appreciated the importance of climate change and ESG compliance for a variety of stakeholders13.,2020.0
942,PingAn_3,"Managers often work under mandates specifying green or ESG com- pliance targets, are under increasing regulatory pressure to disclose the carbon footprint of their holdings and are acutely aware of reputational backlashes.",2020.0
943,PingAn_3,Naive divestment approaches based on blanket policies driven by carbon emissions leave portfolios less diversi- fied and prevent investors from engaging with some of those companies that may play a crucial role in transition- ing to a low-carbon economy (e.,2020.0
944,PingAn_3,"16 Help investors inform and support portfolio tilts: The first objective of developing climate disclosure indicators is to extract more objective information on the climate risk exposure of firms, so as to better inform the portfo- lio tilts an investor may wish to implement in its portfo- lio.",2020.0
945,PingAn_3,"For example, our climate disclosure indicators enable portfolio optimization subject to constraints on disclosure compliance (understood in relation to the TCFD reporting framework) and transparency of particular metrics (e.",2020.0
946,PingAn_3,This approach vastly reduces the inefficiency associated with portfolios result- ing from constrained optimization based on the applica- tion of blanket screens or restrictions driven by simplistic metrics such as carbon footprints (e.,2020.0
947,PingAn_3,"Our results show that, although a carbon risk premium has been documented for high emission firms, the picture is more articulated once climate risk disclosure indicators are taken into account.",2020.0
948,PingAn_3,"As climate awareness gradually increases and climate risk information becomes more granularly available to investors, it is conceivable that we are wit- nessing the transition to a new equilibrium in which mar- kets will eventually price in climate risk information and in- vestors’ preferences.",2020.0
949,PingAn_3,"We find that climate risk disclosures are as sociated with higher valuation of large cap companies, after controlling for emissions, thus suggesting that the valuation dynamics discussed above are more mature for large firms.",2020.0
950,PingAn_3,"Although the scope for appreciation may still be considerable there, we find that small and medium capitalization firms that engage in effective climate risk disclosure may offer the greatest opportunities for superior risk-adjusted returns along the path to efficient climate risk pricing.",2020.0
951,PingAn_3,AI driven indicators could therefore represent a valuable addition to investment policies aiming at making the most of forward-looking metrics of climatic change during the transition to a low carbon economy15.,2020.0
952,PingAn_3,We find that various dimensions of climate disclosure are associated with different firm characteristics and valuations.,2020.0
953,PingAn_3,"For example, a composite climate risk indicator is associated with lower valuations, whereas a composite TCFD financial impact disclosure indicator explains lower leverage and higher valuations.",2020.0
954,PingAn_3,Granular AI indi- cators could further be used to articulate portfolio manag- ers’ views on how climatic risks will shape individual stock returns during the transition to a low carbon economy.,2020.0
